cular flow and pressure. Here we apply CFD modeling to a\nsubject-specific porcine LV model with detailed ventricular structures and\nmotion obtained from previous solid mechanics finite-element (FE) simulations\nbased on high-resolution image data. We simplified the detailed LV endocardial\nsurfaces to remove PM and trabecular structures and built a smoothed model that\nresembles the resolution of in vivo MRI images. We then compare the simulated\nLV flow pattern and pressure of the simplified models to those of the complex\nmodel.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Oct 2019 08:04:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-04"}
{"id":"1911.00318","submitter":"David Zhang","authors":"David K. Zhang","title":"Discovering New Runge-Kutta Methods Using Unstructured Numerical Search","comments":"49 pages; 2 figures; undergraduate thesis written at Vanderbilt\n  University in partial fulfillment of the requirements for the degree of\n  Bachelor of Science with Honors in Mathematics","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA cs.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Runge-Kutta methods are a popular class of numerical methods for solving\nordinary differential equations. Every Runge-Kutta method is characterized by\ntwo basic parameters: its order, which measures the accuracy of the solution it\nproduces, and its number of stages, which measures the amount of computational\nwork it requires. The primary goal in constructing Runge-Kutta methods is to\nmaximize order using a minimum number of stages. However, high-order\nRunge-Kutta methods are difficult to construct because their parameters must\nsatisfy an exponentially large system of polynomial equations. This paper\npresents the first known 10th-order Runge-Kutta method with only 16 stages,\nbreaking a 40-year standing record for the number of stages required to achieve\n10th-order accuracy. It also discusses the tools and techniques that enabled\nthe discovery of this method using a straightforward numerical search.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Oct 2019 05:18:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-11-04"}
